<br>
I played through Unreal 2 a couple a months ago. I interacted with the AI, shot up the ones I didn't like and got a warm fuzzy feeling for saving the day. However in the end, I have no emotional attachment to it.<br>
<br>
When I look back on this period of my life I won't think of the great times I had playing Unreal 2 -- because Unreal 2 is just a game. From EverQuest I have derived much more because it's a social and political environment much like any other place that people congregate; be it a bar, a restaurant, a friend's house or Norrath, these are all places we meet to interact with others. Quake, Counter-Strike and EverQuest have impacted who I know, what I know and who I am.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/brage81292.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pondsfv>PondsFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FaF Standard User</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/20/03 11:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/frage81292frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=930.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sweet mother of jesebus</span><hr size=1> exactly and withweaver hun I do think that  iam not blowing this out of porportion i mean look at the thread Rbnice1 started it had 160ish replys... going on bout nothing in particaular except how wrong this is or how this didnt happen etc... it would be nice to see the 2 factions coincide is just opinion there is more to be gained then lost <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.everydaymind.com/reso/ponds.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/brage81292.showUserPublicProfile?gid=witherweaver>Witherweaver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Math Wiz</span><br>  Posts: 1441<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/21/03 2:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/frage81292frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=930.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sweet mother of jesebus</span><hr size=1> If there's contention over some topic and people have information regarding that, you can expect those people to disclose that information.  This doesn't imply that the topic is of real importance or deep philosophical meaning, it simply means that people have a disagreement, or a mis-(or simply lack of, in some cases) understanding to the extent that conversation is merited to resolve the contention (or, at the very least, get the facts out in the air).<br>
<br>
You are &quot;blowing things out of proportion&quot; in the sense that you're taking this more seriously than it is.  At the end of the day it doesn't really matter if Rbnice1 agrees with us or he doesn't.  He ought not to get offended by what's done here as I see nothing that is offensive.  Likewise with the constituents of those 160ish replies.  <br>
<br>
If you told me something that was blatantly false (actually, it's sufficient for me to simply bleive that what you say is false), I'd debate with you and argue the facts simply for my respect of the truth (assuming that I decided doing so was better than any other course of action at that particular moment).  This doesn't mean that the particular issue is something of great weight or importance, it simply means it's something upon which we disagree.  This thread you started is a beautiful example.<br>
<br>
Your original post was absurd, and that's the thing to which I responded. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>please cant both of your guilds just steer clear and or have some diplomacy between leaders/officers ?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
History, if nothing else, teaches us that Everquest chat isn't a practical medium for diplomacy.  The real issue is that it's a video game that provides a perfect inhabitance for competition, and Fire and Fury and Resolution are guilds that are in competition.  Thus we're always going to be seeing each other because both of us pursuing our own goals and going our own directions will lead to collisions.  There isn't anything inherently wrong or improper with this, it's just the way the game is played. <br>
<br>
The innocent third party &quot;can't we all just get along&quot; perspective annoys me, because we are getting along in the necessary context within the video game.   This third party knows nothing of the opinions and thoughts of the parties involved, but just presumes to know the correct course of action based upon a few select posts from a few select individuals which that party took too seriously in the first place.  <br>
<br>
Specifically, ask yourself this.  What do we have to gain from your said &quot;diplomacy&quot;?  And if it's in both party's benefit to do it, why haven't the done it yet? <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>it would be nice to see the 2 factions coincide is just opinion there is more to be gained then lost<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Specifically, what?  If Fire and Fury was far behind Resolution, then we'd have a lot to gain from making deals and such to ensure our progression through Everquest, assuming of course our goal is to progress through Everquest in what I'll take to be the understood way.  If we were ahead of Resolution but thought they would catch up soon and be in strong competition with us, then we'd benefit from deals and such, since then we wouldn't be trampled on when we aren't in &quot;the lead&quot; (assuming again the same goals).<br>
<br>
But that's not what I (and I think at least some portion of Fire and Fury) feel.  We more feel that we've been fair and just to Resolution, yet constantly get made out to be the bad guys.  So the real question is, what's the benefit for us?<br>
<br>
Resolution is nice people?  Great, I totally agree.  So does most every other member (in the sense that at least one member of each guild can find at least one member of another guild that that person likes).   <br>
<br>
We're nice people too (or, at least, I am).  I have no ill or harmful intentions towards anyone in Resolution or any other guild.  If there's a person I like and get along with, great.  If the person has nothing to offer me I simply am not going to care about them.  I expect other people to treat me the same way.  I make fun of Fire and Fury members a hell of a lot more than I do Resolution members.  Why?  Because it amuses me, and hopefully others as well.  Hence the phrase &quot;make fun&quot; - it's implied that it is something done in jest and not to actually harm.  Jokes are good.<br>
<br>
And also, how are these too factions not &quot;coinciding&quot;?  What exactly do you mean by &quot;coincide&quot;?  The only benefit I see from &quot;a good relationship between the two guilds&quot; in our current state is that nice people get to interact with other nice people, and that's a very nice thing (which is why I brought up the 'nice people' thing, I wasn't referencing something someone else said).  But that's alread happening.  Anyone who is taking guild rivarly personally is being silly, and the rest of us get along just fine.  So what's your problem?  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> good point ponds ...your so smart everyone must love you!/<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The word is &quot;you're&quot;, not &quot;your&quot;.  Why do I say that?  To illistrate my point that I'm simply stating it because it's true, not because it's going to solve the conflict in Iraq (this is, of course, an absurd example used to convey a point, because I like extremes, so don't take it literally).  And my name is &quot;Witherweaver&quot; not &quot;Withweaver&quot;.  And use some punctuation.  And from where did this &quot;pond&quot; come?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>i mean look at the thread Rbnice1 started it had 160ish replys... going on bout nothing in particaular except how wrong this is or how this didnt happen etc...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What is it, exactly, that you want the thread to go on about?  What would you rather have in lieu of that thread?  Isn't it better to pan out what did and did not happen, so everyone is more enlightened in the end?  How does the flow of information harm anyone?<br>
<br>
All in all - what's your point?  What is it that bothers you so much?  What is it you want us to do, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>and how does doing so benefit us?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Finally, and this is more in response to Treskin's post, there's no real difference between &quot;Everquest&quot; and &quot;Real life&quot; in the literal sense.  By this I mean that recreation and social interaction is part of real life, and everquest is both recreation and social interaction.  But there is a difference in the sense that &quot;real life&quot; involves some things that aren't of fundamental importance.  Once you have a serious outlook on life, you realize there's some things which aren't so serious - there are some things that are there <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>simply for amusement, entertainment, and enjoyment</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  <br>
<br>
If you're on a sports team and you feel your teamates and opponents act in such a way that makes the game unenjoyable as a matter of your personal opinion, then you should find a new set of people or a new game.  You shouldn't threaten them with physical violence or a rifle over a cup of coffee (this is, of course, in reference to Kiluen's post).  This is what I think, for instance, Kurley means when he says that real life is not the same as EQ.  Perhaps the position would be better said as &quot;recreation doesn't warrant personal offense&quot;. <br>
<br>
